<li id="cite_note-7"><b><a href="#cite_ref-7" title="">^</a></b> The fact that Proctor forgets this particular commandment creates <a href="/wiki/Irony" title="Irony">irony</a> because the audience, along with Proctor and Elizabeth, realises that he also forgot the commandment when he had his affair with Abigail. As he has failed to incorporate it into his life, it fails to remain in his memory.</li>
<li id="cite_note-Blakesley-8"><b><a href="#cite_ref-Blakesley_8-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFMiller1992">Miller, Arthur (1992). "A note on the historical accuracy of the play". in Blakesley, Maureen. <i>The Crucible, a play in four acts</i>. Oxford, England: Heinemann. xvii. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0435232819" class="internal">ISBN 0435232819</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=A+note+on+the+historical+accuracy+of+the+play&amp;rft.atitle=The+Crucible%2C+a+play+in+four+acts&amp;rft.aulast=Miller&amp;rft.aufirst=Arthur&amp;rft.au=Miller%2C+Arthur&amp;rft.date=1992&amp;rft.pages=xvii&amp;rft.place=Oxford%2C+England&amp;rft.pub=Heinemann&amp;rft.isbn=0435232819&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:The_Crucible"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
</ol>
</div>
